-NõW<?php exit; ?>a:1:{s:7:"content";O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:4:"1561";s:11:"post_author";s:2:"48";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-02-28 15:24:08";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-02-28 15:24:08";s:12:"post_content";s:1391:"<strong>February 28th 2014:</strong> The United Nations General Assembly have announced Monday 3<sup>rd</sup> March 2014 as the first ever World Wildlife Day. Secretary General to CITES (Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species) John E. Scanlon marks the event as an ‚Äúopportunity for all of us ‚Äì no matter who we are or where we are ‚Äì to celebrate the beauty and variety of the millions of plants and animals that we share our planet with‚Äù.

There is no doubt our wildlife is suffering from severe habitat loss and threats due to the illegal trade, but amidst the current crisis and the toll this is taking on economies, livelihoods and habitats across the globe, World Wildlife Day offers a chance for those around the world to step back and recognise just how precious our natural environment is.

"We invite all member States, relevant organizations of the United Nations system as well as all other interested organizations and individuals - from airports to museums to schools - to get involved in this global celebration of wildlife", added Scanlon.

<a title="WWD" href="http://www.wildlifeday.org/" target="_blank">Find out more.</a>

